<div class="text-row reveal">
  <h4 class="f6 tracked black-50 ttu fw4">Digital Wireframes</h4>
  <p>
    In the phase of digital wireframing I wanted to diverge as much as possible and created 3 different wireframe journeys before I was happy with the final version. The 3 different wireframes considered different scenarios, such as using a check-in system to the restaurant. Using NFC devices, and finally using a schedule system using Google's My Business.
  </p>
  <p><mark>This is where things get interesting</mark></p>
  <p>
    The final wireframe journey was an much more realistic approach to the problem. Going back to my user research I realised that restaurants were hesitant introducing extra work load to their already busy schedule. Such as bringing a NFC device onto the table in order for the customer to give feedback. My new updated journey would put the ball in the court of the customer.
  </p>
  <p class="f2">
    Google Maps already has vast amount of data about restaurants around the world. So my idea is to directly integrate the design solution as an integral part of Google Maps. I call it the <mark>Integrated Approach</mark>
  </p>
  <p>
    Because most of the workload of reviewing a waiter is delegated to the customer I discovered that a lot of constraints and assumptions where automagically solved. Such as identifying if a restaurant has waiters at all. Some food places are simply a hole-in-the-wall type and have no external service.
  </p>
  <p>
    A constraint to consider: How to deal with restaurants with lots of waiters? Ideally when the user is ready to give service feedback, they are presented only with the waiters that they interacted with. To solve this issue partially I've included some design thinking around what the business owners can do to help solve that issue. Google already has the My Business platform where they can edit various aspects of their business listing. Using the platform; business owners can define a schedule for their employees. Meaning that when customers are presented with a list of waiters, they only see the ones working on that particular day
  </p>
  <p>
    The integrated approach also solved the problem of making sure all restaurants had the latest technology such as scanning a NFC tag, or even a QR code. This meant that this solution will work for any restaurants around the world. No matter how remote they might be</p>
  </p>
  <p>
    During my research I identified that only certain user types would actively review businesses. The integrated approach makes sure that users arent forced to leave a review if they are not that type of user.
  </p>
</div>

